00:00:00.499 --> 00:00:02.630
LAURENCE MORONEY: Welcome
to the Googleplex.

00:00:02.630 --> 00:00:05.170
This is an incredible place
with lots of great stuff being

00:00:05.170 --> 00:00:08.039
worked on every single day.

00:00:08.039 --> 00:00:09.940
Before I worked here,
I always wondered

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:12.250
what it would be like to
come to the Googleplex,

00:00:12.250 --> 00:00:14.830
meet up with a Googler,
and have coffee with them,

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:17.240
and just chat about what
they do, how they do it,

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:18.420
and why they do it.

00:00:18.420 --> 00:00:20.340
And today we're going
to do exactly that.

00:00:23.532 --> 00:00:24.990
Welcome to "Coffee
With a Googler."

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:26.220
I'm Laurence
Moroney, and I'm here

00:00:26.220 --> 00:00:27.620
today in New York
City, where I'm

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:30.320
meeting with Ray Tsang
from the cloud team.

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:32.920
Now Ray, you've been working
on this awesome project called

00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:36.400
Cloud Spin, which is effectively
using a bunch of Android phones

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:38.460
and building bullet
time from the matrix.

00:00:38.460 --> 00:00:39.870
Could you tell us all about it?

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.760
RAY TSANG: Sure, yeah,
so a team of four

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:46.200
us, we built these bullet
time demo called Cloud Spin.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:47.670
It was actually
designed in built

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:51.426
for our event series called
the Google Cloud Platform Next.

00:00:51.426 --> 00:00:52.800
And we actually
toured the world.

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:54.580
We went to a bunch
of different cities,

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:56.560
and we took this
experience to there

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:58.680
so that people can
actually experience

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:00.610
what Google Cloud can do.

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:03.180
So built this demo that used
many of the Google Cloud

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:08.770
technology that will take a
photo from 19 different Android

00:01:08.770 --> 00:01:12.850
phones, and at exactly
the same moment of you

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:14.661
jumping in midair.

00:01:14.661 --> 00:01:16.160
And then we can
stitch them together

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:18.280
in the Google Cloud
Platform and to form

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:19.992
this 180-degrees spinning photo.

00:01:19.992 --> 00:01:22.200
LAURENCE MORONEY: So it's
like an animated GIF of all

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:23.430
these pictures put together?

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:24.846
RAY TSANG: Yeah,
so eventually, we

00:01:24.846 --> 00:01:27.750
produce this animated GIF
that gets posted on Twitter,

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:29.695
or it gets sent through
email to the audience.

00:01:29.695 --> 00:01:31.070
LAURENCE MORONEY:
Cool, so now we

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:32.970
actually went to where you
built the prototype of this,

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:34.136
and we filmed a video of it.

00:01:34.136 --> 00:01:35.870
So why don't we
run that video now.

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:37.270
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:39.500
-Hi, I'm Brett McGowen, and
I'm a developer advocate

00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:41.160
for the Google Cloud Platform.

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:43.230
One of our goals
of this project was

00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:45.820
to use all off-the-shelf
hardware and open source

00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:48.530
software so that anyone
could create their own cloud

00:01:48.530 --> 00:01:49.380
spin set up.

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.900
The hardware in this room
consists of 18 camera tripods.

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:55.400
On top of these camera tripods,
we have special adapters

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:58.160
to hold our Nexus 6 cameras.

00:01:58.160 --> 00:01:59.990
We position all of
the cameras eight feet

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:02.073
from the center point,
where the user is standing.

00:02:02.073 --> 00:02:04.110
This lets the user jump
up as high as they can

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:05.550
and still remain on screen.

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:08.270
Once we've got all the
cameras set up and plugged in,

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:09.300
we need to align them.

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:11.450
We do this by taking
a marker pole,

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:14.010
marking it two places with
tape, and setting it where

00:02:14.010 --> 00:02:15.170
the user is going to stand.

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:16.840
Then on the back
of the camera we've

00:02:16.840 --> 00:02:19.370
got cross hairs that we can
use to align to the two points

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:20.530
on the marker pole.

00:02:20.530 --> 00:02:23.530
This lets us align the view
in multiple dimensions.

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:26.520
Once the cameras are all
aligned, we need a volunteer.

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:29.070
Hi, would you like to sign
up for a Cloud Spin video?

00:02:29.070 --> 00:02:35.028
-Sure, sounds good-- so
name, I put my email address

00:02:35.028 --> 00:02:37.092
and on my Twitter.

00:02:37.092 --> 00:02:39.050
Oh, cool, so you can post
it to Twitter for me.

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:39.770
-Exactly.

00:02:39.770 --> 00:02:42.230
-And I'll be good, I agree
to the terms of service,

00:02:42.230 --> 00:02:43.220
and sign up.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:43.890
-Perfect.

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:46.820
Using Firebase, the sign-up
app will send his registration

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:48.240
information to our control app.

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:50.380
Out control app uses
Firebase to show

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:53.440
the status of every phone that's
connected to the Cloud Spin

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:53.940
system.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:57.290
We'll also use our control app
to push out different settings

00:02:57.290 --> 00:03:00.290
to the phone, such as
exposure or shutter speed,

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:02.520
so that as we get into
different lighting conditions,

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:04.630
we can control those
settings in one place

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:06.900
and have all the cameras
automatically update.

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:08.900
Now that we're ready,
we'll hit Start Countdown.

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:11.390
So this will send a time
stamp to all the phones

00:03:11.390 --> 00:03:14.250
so that they know the exact
moment, eight seconds from now,

00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:15.760
when to be recording video.

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:18.120
The control app has a
button called Take Photo.

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:20.220
When we press this,
a beep is sent out

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:22.370
through the audio jack
of the control tablet

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:27.200
and is split 18 ways to go into
the headset jack of each phone.

00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:30.180
This will mark the frame at
the exact same moment of time

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:32.170
across all the cameras.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:34.220
Once each camera is finished
recording its video,

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:36.130
it'll upload it to
Google Cloud Storage.

00:03:36.130 --> 00:03:38.640
So we can process in the
cloud, extract all the frames,

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:41.100
stitch it together, and
create our final animation.

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:43.770
All right, step into the center,
and I'll get out of the way.

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:50.600
One, two, three, go.

00:03:53.635 --> 00:03:55.060
[END PLAYBACK]

