00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:25.950
LAURENCE MORONEY: One
of the remarkable things

00:05:25.950 --> 00:05:28.105
about the picture is like
it's pretty accurate where

00:05:28.105 --> 00:05:29.313
the pictures were taken from.

00:05:29.313 --> 00:05:31.230
So must have had to
measure it quite well

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.050
around a semicircle
with the same radius

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:35.350
to each camera's lens.

00:05:35.350 --> 00:05:36.184
How did you do that?

00:05:36.184 --> 00:05:38.599
RAY TSANG: So there are a
couple things that we have done.

00:05:38.599 --> 00:05:40.250
So first of all, we
have to figure out

00:05:40.250 --> 00:05:44.030
how far away the camera needs
to be from the center point

00:05:44.030 --> 00:05:47.140
so that we can actually
capture the person jumping.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:48.980
Because if you're
too close, the head

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:50.485
will be cut off in the video.

00:05:50.485 --> 00:05:52.860
LAURENCE MORONEY: You don't
want that, only in the video,

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:53.410
though, right.

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:54.868
RAY TSANG: Only in
the video, yeah,

00:05:54.868 --> 00:05:57.980
but then we had to measure
how far the camera needs to be

00:05:57.980 --> 00:05:59.800
far away from the center point.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:02.510
And initially, we
actually couldn't

00:06:02.510 --> 00:06:04.980
find a measuring tape
in the Google office

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:06.610
at all to do the measurement.

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:09.870
And for some reason, Brett
actually found caution tapes

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:10.570
around my desk.

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:12.611
Now, I don't know why I
have those police caution

00:06:12.611 --> 00:06:14.937
tapes around my desk,
but so he found it,

00:06:14.937 --> 00:06:16.520
and then we measured
it with cautions.

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:20.232
And I think he said that we
need to be eight cautions away.

00:06:20.232 --> 00:06:21.940
LAURENCE MORONEY: So
eight cautions away,

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:22.950
that's the management, OK.

00:06:22.950 --> 00:06:24.330
BRETT MCGOWEN: Yeah,
but eventually we

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:26.720
found like real measuring tapes,
and then we measured it out.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.770
LAURENCE MORONEY: So was
eight cautions accurate?

00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:31.190
RAY TSANG: It was
about eight feet.

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:32.340
LAURENCE MORONEY: Now, one
of the things I noticed,

00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:33.555
and what Brett was talking
about in the video,

00:06:33.555 --> 00:06:35.013
is you didn't
actually take photos.

00:06:35.013 --> 00:06:36.296
You took videos.

00:06:36.296 --> 00:06:37.670
I know like a
video obviously has

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:39.544
a number frames, like,
24, 30 frames a second

00:06:39.544 --> 00:06:40.319
or whatever it is.

00:06:40.319 --> 00:06:42.610
So you have to pick out the
right frame from the video.

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:44.830
And he said you had
an audio cue for that,

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:46.760
so will you tell us
a little about that?

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:51.270
RAY TSANG: Sure, so first
of all, taking the photo

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:53.580
from each of the phones is
going to be very difficult

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:55.620
if we want to take the
photo all at exactly

00:06:55.620 --> 00:06:58.210
the same time because
there is this random delay

00:06:58.210 --> 00:06:59.550
in the hardware.

00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:02.256
So when you want to take
the photo from the phone,

00:07:02.256 --> 00:07:03.630
you just don't
know how much time

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:06.824
is going to wait before the
photo's actually being taken.

00:07:06.824 --> 00:07:08.240
And if we have
these random delays

00:07:08.240 --> 00:07:11.630
from all of the 19 phones, then
we will be taking photos of you

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:13.610
jumping in midair, or
where you landed already.

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.080
LAURENCE MORONEY: They
won't be synchronized.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:16.330
RAY TSANG: Yeah, exactly.

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:19.540
So rather than doing that,
we recorded the video.

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:22.680
And to synchronize all of them
together, we used audio cue.

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:25.980
So I as the videos are rlling,
and when you're in the midair,

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:28.560
we generate a tone,
an audio tone,

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:31.230
that gets fed into
all of the devices.

00:07:31.230 --> 00:07:34.110
And, oh, by the way, we
actually thought about doing--

00:07:34.110 --> 00:07:37.360
LAURENCE MORONEY: It's the
Flying Spaghetti monster.

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:40.740
RAY TSANG: Or
whatever, yeah-- so it

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:44.560
was very difficult to actually
feed audio signal from, say,

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:48.040
the tablet that's generating
the tone into the 19 devices.

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:50.500
So now an audio
engineer actually

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:53.550
drew a schema, how
to actually build

00:07:53.550 --> 00:07:56.960
a device that can help us
split the audio signal.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.990
And another difficult
thing to do this

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:02.290
is that when you plug in the
audio line, the audio cable,

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:06.300
the device has to be able to
recognize that this is a mic.

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:08.560
So to do that, we
built this device where

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:10.230
the audio kind of
comes in one way,

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:12.064
and then we split it
into 19 different ways.

00:08:12.064 --> 00:08:13.146
LAURENCE MORONEY: Oh, fun.

00:08:13.146 --> 00:08:15.480
RAY TSANG: Yeah, and we
got like these resistors

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:18.210
and whatever that kind of
generates the right resistance

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:20.210
so that the mic is being
picked up by the phone.

00:08:20.210 --> 00:08:22.084
LAURENCE MORONEY: So
resistance isn't futile?

00:08:22.084 --> 00:08:25.010
RAY TSANG: Yeah,
but unfortunately,

00:08:25.010 --> 00:08:28.070
it is futile because this device
unfortunately didn't work.

00:08:28.070 --> 00:08:29.832
LAURENCE MORONEY: Oh.

00:08:29.832 --> 00:08:32.770
RAY TSANG: Yeah, so rather doing
that, we actually just went

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:35.440
out and bought off-the-shelf
components that can help

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:37.064
us split the singnal.

00:08:37.064 --> 00:08:38.480
LAURENCE MORONEY:
OK, sounds good.

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:40.146
Now, one of the things
I noticed as well

00:08:40.146 --> 00:08:41.741
is that like all
these phones, they

00:08:41.741 --> 00:08:43.990
have to be synchronized in
when they start this video.

00:08:43.990 --> 00:08:45.620
So they had to be
remote controlled,

00:08:45.620 --> 00:08:48.470
and I hear you had a
really fun, innovative way

00:08:48.470 --> 00:08:50.050
of using Firebase to do that.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.060
BRETT MCGOWEN: Right,
so rather than, say,

00:08:52.060 --> 00:08:54.680
building our own server
and sending our own network

00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:57.330
signal to all of the
devices-- remember,

00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:58.920
we only had about three weeks.

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:01.790
And you do something
custom to send the single

00:09:01.790 --> 00:09:05.470
to all these devices, it's
going to take us a lot of time.

00:09:05.470 --> 00:09:08.550
So rather than doing
that, we used Firebase.

00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:12.800
And the way that we have used it
is to send out from the tablet

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:15.340
when you press the button
to start the countdown,

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:18.170
we actually write
the timestamp of when

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:22.210
the video should be starting
to recording into Firebase.

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:25.190
And then Firebase then
can synchronize the data

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:27.560
to all of the 19
different devices.

00:09:27.560 --> 00:09:30.050
So every single device,
every single Android phone

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:33.030
at this moment, they receive
a signal from Firebase

00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:36.710
with the timestamp of when the
video should start rolling,

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:39.330
and all the devices then
will start recording

00:09:39.330 --> 00:09:41.319
the video at about
the same time.

00:09:41.319 --> 00:09:43.110
LAURENCE MORONEY: Cool,
really fun project,

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:44.526
you've done a lot
of work on this,

00:09:44.526 --> 00:09:46.884
and if developers want
to take advantage of this

00:09:46.884 --> 00:09:49.300
or do some this itself, are
there any resources out there?

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.633
Have you blogged, or do you
have source code or anything

00:09:51.633 --> 00:09:52.150
like that?

